loc: Freshwater Lake, Barrow, North Slope Borough, Alaska
rmk: natural vocalizations; calls from a group of four females and one male bird on a medium sized shallow pond in wet tundra.  These vocalizations are all given after three female birds flew into the pond that had formerly been occupied by only the male and one female, and all of the birds were interacting.  Most of these calls are given as all give birds are perched on the edge of the pond and most of the females were actively engaged in head-lift displays at each other.  The resident pair seemed to be somewhat aggressive towards the three interloper females, but I believe most of the calls were by these interlopers.  Note especially the low 'coo' call from the male at 0:01, 0:34, and 1:14; I believe these to be the first recordings of male calls from this species.  Also note the more drawn out, groaning quack calls, more evident near the end of the cut.  I am unsure if these are from the male or female birds, but I suspect they are from the females, and these calls appear to be undescribed.  A rather unfortunate amount of wind noise audible in this cut.
